as brought to Ulster, Ireland, from Scotland in the 17th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Tod","meanings":["Scottish (mainly Midlothian): variant of   Todd  ."]},{"name":"Todhunter","meanings":["English (Cumbria and Lancashire): nickname for a keen hunter of foxes, from Middle English <i>tod(de)</i> ‘fox’ + Middle English <i>hunter(e)</i> (see   Hunter   and   Todman  )."]}]},{"name":"Sarah","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the wife of Abraham and mother of Isaac. According to the Book of Genesis, she was originally called <i>Sarai</i> (possibly meaning ‘contentious’ in Hebrew), but had her name changed by God to the more auspicious <i>Sarah</i> ‘princess’ in token of a greater blessing (Genesis 17:15, ‘And God said unto Abraham, As for Sarai thy wife, thou shalt not call her name Sarai, but Sarah shall her name be’). This has been one of the most enduringly popular girls' names."],"variants":[{"name":"Sara","meanings":["Variant of   Sarah .  This is the form used in the Greek of the New Testament (Hebrews 11:11)."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":7,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Sarah Todd was born in 1375, in Cranbrook, Kent, England as the daughter of Todd. She had at least 1 son with Thomas Hendley. She died in 1435, in her hometown, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1375–1435":"1375–1435","1400–1472":"1400–1472","1355–Male":"1355–Surnud","1435":"1435","1400":"1400","1355":"1355","1375":"1375","about 1400":"umbes 1400","1472":"1472","1382